AGI - Flags and memorabilia in Piazza Podestà in Varese for 40 years of the Lombard League. The polemical words pronounced by Umberto Bossi against the leadership of Matteo Salvini seem not to have cast out the unity of the League. On the stage of the event, in the midst of hundreds of militants and dozens of party flags, next to the secretary Matteo Salvini have taken the word the ministers loyalists Giancarlo Giorgetti, Roberto Calderoli, Giuseppe Valditara, the group leader in the Senate Massimiliano Romeo, the governor Attilio Fontana and the coordinator of the League Lombarda Fabrizio Cecchetti. After Bossi attacked him yesterday from the feast of Gemonio ("the League serves a new leader"), Salvini tried to lower the tones: "without Umberto Bossi today we wouldn't be here."
&nbsp;
The secretary, he claimed, "I do it at the best of my chances for 10 years with soul, time and heart." On the absence of the senatur at the feast of Varese, Salvini revealed: "I invited him, he made other choices, that's fine. In Bossi, since he built everything, everything is allowed." Then he remembered: "I've been in League for 30 years and I'm used to night and day calls of insult and polemic by Umberto Bossi, so I need to understand and improve."
&nbsp;
Salvini also thanked Roberto Maroni "for what he taught me so much". Ministers and speakers have spent words in support of the leadership of Salvini. Giorgetti, in particular, said: "There were incredible people, able to interpret their time and their people who taught us how to go on that winding ground. Thanks to the militants and Bossi, to Matteo who carries out this battle, to Maroni who is no longer there". But he also added that the "principles of hierarchy and discipline", "they must not become servilism. That would be a mistake. These are rules that make us strong and certain that at the top we will arrive."
&nbsp;
The group leader Romeo, instead, after saying that we must be "free" to the secretary, added that "this party is the right opportunity to rediscover a little identity, origins and sense of belonging, we must mainly start from the territory and the militants trying to listen to them a little more". A request to listen to the base also comes from the group leader to the Chamber, Riccardo Molinari. No doubt for the Minister of Education, Giuseppe Valditara: the League "must go ahead with Matteo Salvini", because his direction "is the right one".&nbsp;

